default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDo you think sentence length is a valid proxy for deciding which prisoners get the right to vote?
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is the best proxy for offence seriousness, and is preferable to a scheme which excludes certain prisoners, i
default.
defaulte
default.,
default those convicted of personal injury offences. Yet sentence length is still a poor tool to distinguish between prisoners in order to determine who should be disenfranchised. There is no point on the dimension of sentence length which provides a cut
default-
defaultoff which is anything but arbitrary. The few correctional regimes that use sentence length – such as Canada – did so drawing upon an important
default division of jurisdiction. Thus in Canada, federal prisoners – those serving two years or longer were disenfranchised, while provincial prisoners retained the vote. The federal provincial correctional bifurcation in jurisdiction split in Canada was important but has no 
defaultequivalent 
defaultcounterpart in England and Wales. (In addition the disenfranchisement of federal prisoners 
defaultin Canada 
defaultwas ultimately struck down on constitutional grounds
default in R. v. Sauve)
default. The closest alternative 
defaultin England 
defaultwould be the Magistrate/ Crown court division but using this as the division would 
defaultin our view 
defaultbe overbroad: federal prisoners in Canada represented only 
defaultapproximately 
default3% of the 
defaulttotal Canadian 
defaultprison population; prisoners sentenced from the Crown Court represent a 
defaultsignificantly
default higher percentage of the total prisoner population.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultOur preferred approach would involve 
defaulttwo 
defaultsteps:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat, if anything, is the 
defaultsignificance of four
default years and/or six months in the sentencing of criminals? 
default&#xa0;
defaultAs noted, there is no significance; both are arbitrary thresholds.
default&#xa0;
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIf you were to draw a line between serious and non-serious offences using sentence length, where would it be?
default&#xa0;
defaultWe would not draw the line, but one possibility would be to disenfranchise anyone sentenced to life imprisonment
default on the grounds that they have committed a crime of such seriousness that the most severe penalty was warranted
default.
default&#xa0;
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCan you think of an example where the sentence length approach could lead to an anomalous result? (For example, electoral fraud may result in a short sentence.)
defaultMany cases heard at the Crown Court involve several counts, some relating to the same incident, some relating to completely separate incidents. If a threshold relating to sentence length is applied clear rules will be needed about the way in which total sentence is calculated. Clearly it would be anomalous to sum concurrent sentences, but 
defaultmore 
defaultrational to do so for consecutive ones
default.
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt has been suggested by Liberty that the disenfranchisement of prisoners disproportionately impacts on ethnic minority communities. Is this correct?
defaultAny groups that are less likely than others to secure sentencing discounts – eg for early guilty pleas or for expressing remorse will – other things being equal – be more likely to be disenfranchised. There is evidence that BME groups are 
defaultless likelydefault to enter early guilty pleas.
default&#xa0;
defaultPeople nearing the end of their criminal careers – aiming to find a route out of crime – may by virtue of their long record actually be sentenced more heavily than those who are not trying to stop. This group may be over-represented.
default&#xa0;
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAccording to a note from the House of Commons Library,
default 
defaultapproximately a quarter of those sentenced to less than four years have been convicted of a violent or sexual offence.
default&#xa0;
default Under what circumstances would someone convicted of these types of offences be sentenced to less than four years?
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultAs noted, we are of the view that 
defaultall 
defaultcategory-based exclusions are unwise. Why would you want to disenfranchise someone convicted of a crime of violence against a single individual 
defaultbut
default not someone who has deprived dozens of elderly victims of their life savings 
defaultyet
default who is convicted of a property crime? Crime seriousness is a better yardstick
default than offence category
default, but as we noted, there is no non-arbitrary cut
default-
defaultoff. 
defaultBut to address the question directly, many offenders convicted of a crime of violence would be sentenced to much less than 4 years. For example, the guideline range for common assault carries a ceiling of 26 weeks.
default Section 47 assaults are divided in the 
defaultdefinitive sentencing 
defaultguideline into 3 categories of seriousness, each with its own sentence range. The sentence range for the most serious category (1) is from 1-3 years.
default The guidelines for less serious sexual assault involving an adult victim has starting points that span the custody threshold.
